meta: | theme: technical | type: readme | project: @dotit/core | version: 1.25.0

title: @dotit/core
summary: IntentText parser, validator, renderer, and document engine. Zero-dependency plain-text document format for contracts, reports, and workflows.

section: Installation
code: npm install @dotit/core

section: Quick Start
text: Parse a document, validate it, and render to HTML:
code: import { parseIntentText, checkConformance, renderHTML } from '@dotit/core';

const doc = parseIntentText(source);
const conformance = checkConformance(doc, { level: 'lax' });
const html = renderHTML(doc, { theme: 'corporate' });

section: API Reference
sub: parseIntentText(source)
text: Parses raw `.it` source into a structured document object. Returns `{ document, errors }`.

sub: checkConformance(doc, options)
text: Validates document against format rules. Options: `{ level: 'lax' | 'strict' }`. Returns `{ conformant, errors, warnings, issues }`.

sub: renderHTML(doc, options)
text: Renders document to HTML fragment. Options: `{ theme: string }`.

sub: renderPrint(doc, options)
text: Renders print-ready HTML with @page rules, running headers/footers, and page breaks.

sub: sealDocument(source, options)
text: Computes SHA-256 hash and appends `freeze:` line. Returns `{ success, hash, source, at }`.

section: Configuration
| Option | Type | Default | Description |
| theme | string | 'minimal' | Document theme: corporate, legal, editorial, technical, minimal, warm, dark, print |
| level | string | 'lax' | Conformance level: lax or strict |
| missing | string | 'keep' | Template merge behavior: keep, blank, or error |

section: Document Structure
text: A `.it` file is a sequence of intent lines. Each line starts with a keyword followed by a colon:
- `title:` — document title
- `section:` — major section
- `sub:` — subsection
- `text:` — paragraph
- `metric:` — key-value metric with optional target/trend/period
- `task:` — action item with owner and due date
- `decision:` — recorded decision with author and date

info: Custom keywords are first-class. Invent domain-specific terms like `clause:`, `risk:`, or `sla:` instead of flattening everything into `text:`. | type: warning

